fields.text: +HyperOpinionatedOk.  I don't really understand your point.  Yes, a religious person might explain the pilot's action as "free will," which means that God didn't specifically will this event to happen.  But that same religious person might at another time, when convenient, say that a different happening is God's doing (when it is something good) or Satan's doing (when it is something bad).  So whether this was actually a case of "free will" for the pilot is not germane to my point.  I'm not a philosopher.  I am merely pointing out that religion necessitates contradictions and hypocrisy in order to explain the unexplainable in ways that will best soothe a gullible public (and bilk them for money). fields.author: Steve G
fields.text: 1.  I'm not.  The fedora is unrelated.2.  Nothing about Brian Williams' lies that got him suspended actually changed any situation going forward.  They were events he embellished to make better stories, apparently.  Bill O'Reilly uses his fraudulent "expertise" on war coverage, etc., to try to shape ongoing policies and to deepen the political biases in his audience.  If I tell you that a group is gaining traction in a few cities in Oman, and that this is a cause worth going to war for, chances are that you will shrug and ignore me.  If I tell you that I was standing next to a group of barbarians who were hacking people to death and raping women, and this is the most evil group imaginable and thus I have been convinced that war is the only option, you are much more likely to trust me, because I am an eyewitness with a firsthand account, so my insight means more than someone just relaying a story from a distance.  O'Reilly isn't some retired old man who is embellishing something irrelevant about the old truck he used to own.  People turn to the network news and the cable news channels to form opinions about our policies, and then they elect officials based upon those opinions.  No one's opinion of the Iraq War will change based on where Brian Williams was.  But someone's opinion of our foreign policy could change if a journalist speaks candidly of events that so clearly paint "good vs. evil" that it sharpens the listener's resolve.  It is part of the reason that reporters become famous--because they are there covering events and observing them in a way that we cannot.  O'Reilly's lies are far more impactful.3.  I went out of my way to not be ideological in my criticism of Brian Williams.  Just because you like an anchor or a network or that network's political biases more or less than the alternative doesn't mean that every story has to be drowning in partisan hackery.  I don't care if Williams ever gets his job back, because NBC, just like the other mainstream news outlets (including FOX), is a hack for the Establishment.  Williams, or the next person or the next person, are going to tell the same pro-Establishment lies, and that is the real problem.  Fox will tell Republican pro-Establishment lies, NBC will tell Democratic pro-Establishment lies, and these impactful lies will fly under the radar because people happen to catch IRRELEVANT lies and make examples out of them to boost their bogus integrity.

fields.author: Steve G
fields.text: +HyperOpinionatedAlso no.  But you are the one that made this distinction.  There is no reason you had to mention that Williams was "news" and O'Reilly was "opinion" unless you are using different standards to judge their guilt.  There shouldn't be different standards, because lying is not one of the leeways permitted to an analyst just because he/she is editorializing.I think that O'Reilly's lies are far worse than Williams' in these two specific cases, but it has nothing to do with ideology.  To prove this, I think that Brian Williams' has had far worse lies as a simple matter of course in being a MSM news anchor.  As was mentioned on TYT, Williams brought on retired generals to shill for the Iraq War without disclosing that they were getting paid by defense contractors and had a financial incentive to push for war.  That is MUCH worse than claiming he saw a dead body during Katrina when in fact someone three or four blocks away undoubtedly saw a dead body.  Williams has surely covered issues like Social Security's solvency and "clean coal technology" in a 50/50 way (Democrats say this, Republicans say this), when the facts are that Social Security has a giant surplus for 20 more years and there is no such thing as clean coal, and covering them as though there is debate is a massive disservice to the truth.  Surely he must have "reported" that Obama ended the Iraq War in 2011, when in fact Bush ended it with his timeline in 2008 and Obama tried to stay longer than 2011 and was rebuffed by the Iraqi government.  These lies are significant because they sway people's votes and affect real policy.  Whether Williams' helicopter was shot at or the helicopter in front of him was shot at doesn't affect anything.  O'Reilly, however, uses his fraudulent gravitas about having been in war zones he wasn't in to bully his guests and present an ideological narrative about how evil some people are, as he witnessed first-hand (though he didn't), and why we therefore need to build support for more war, and look upon opposing views as un-American, cowardly and contemptuous.  This actually does affect public discourse.By the way, in the first three "real" lies I cite of Williams, he was/is doing the bidding of Conservatives.  In the fourth, he was/is doing the bidding of Obama.  That's the point--his ideology doesn't matter at all to my analysis.  You just want to a "Liberal Media Conspiracy" narrative, simply because you don't like that O'Reilly has done something worse with this spate of lies than Williams did.

Despite cannons being available, capable of destroying a building in a single shot and killing dozens, were they limited by the Second Amendment?"No. Threatening people is classed as assault."That's not an argument.For instance, in Oregon, "Publicly insulting such other person by abusive words or gestures in a manner intended and *likely to provoke a violent response*"Subjects another to alarm by conveying a false report, known by the conveyor to be false, concerning death or serious physical injury to a person, *which report reasonably would be expected to cause alarm*;"Subjects another to alarm by conveying a telephonic, electronic or written threat to inflict serious physical injury on that person or to commit a felony involving the person or property of that person or any member of that persons family, *which threat reasonably would be expected to cause alarm.*"Every state whose laws are Constitutional have this caveat of burden of proof on the prosecution. So a common colloquialism like, "Fuck you," is not valid for charges of assault for being in fear of imminent rape, because speech itself is not regulated.

fields.author: nexus1g
fields.text: +Hal Jordan First of all, do you even know what gun I'm talking about that was presented to the Founding Fathers? You see, what you forget is that the Founding Fathers were seeing firearms take the front stage in warfare, transitioning from the bladed weapon. They knew better than we even do today the frightening jumps in power armaments can make in a relatively short period of time. We're still using a lot of 70-year-old technology in modern firearms.No, threatening someone is not in itself illegal, as I said. Again, *as I said*, the burden of proof of the person pressing charges is to prove that a reasonable person would expect the threat to be acted on. So, again, it is the action that's being legislated, not the speech.

fields.author: Steve G
fields.text: +Mathew ClemenceWe are not an advocacy group for policy changes.  We want for the delegates from the various states to hammer out the details to best solve the problem as they see fit.  I personally have some preferences of what I would like to see, but it is only our job to get this to a Convention.  After seeing the language of the Amendment(s) proposed, it will be up to our leadership to determine whether we'd like to try to get the proposal ratified, in order to become law.  This isn't a perfectly rosy answer, but we believe that if there are good ideas out there, given the absence of corruption by money, they will find their way to the surface, and we are the bouncers that will keep money out of the process while the adults talk inside.  We aren't looking to have a seat at the table ourselves.  Therefore, I can't say that Wolf-PAC specifically advocates or criticizes your preferred solution for allocation of money.  We aren't an ideological lobbying organization.Also, there are lots of issues that we feel can be taken care of by passing normal laws.  The problem is that the system is so drowned in money that people never have honest debates, and (broadly) the people whose money gives them such power don't really want to fix the system, because they get rich from the system.  Voting reform can happen after we get the money out of the system as much as possible, but it really can't happen before we do this, because there is too much corruption.  Rules restricting the "revolving door" between regulatory agencies and the industries they are supposed to regulate, as another example, can be proposed after we get the money out of politics, but it has no chance of passing before we do this.  There are other organizations that can try to push for these things if Wolf-PAC disappears because our job is complete.I know of no plans to extend Wolf-PAC beyond the borders of the United States at this time.

fields.author: sdrawkcabgnipytmi
fields.text: +Aust duhe I asked you to provide a peer reviewed paper from a non biased source. There are a number of levels on which you failed here:Firstly, the Library of Economics and Liberty has an ideological agenda that goes directly against the kinds of regulations that would be necessary to reduce our CO2 output. In what world is this a non-biased source?Secondly, I asked for a peer reviewed paper, this is just what some guy posed on his political website.Thirdly you misunderstood my request. I didn't ask for a source where the consensus figure is debunked, I asked you for a climate research paper that disputes that man made warming doesn't happen. If there's no consensus, as you claim, then the scientific literature should be full of them. Lastly, the article you referenced is absurd to begin with. The study it's referring to examined the positions of climate scientists in their abstract. Turns out that most of them didn't say anything about whether man made global warming is real. Does that mean they don't hold the view? Of course not. It would be absurd for them to have to state this well known fact in every single abstract of a climate science paper. Should they also have to state the fact that water can exist as a solid, liquid and gas? The article states that "so 64 out of 11,944, or 0.5%, take the view that humans are the main cause of global warming." Okay if this biased bullshit is correct, please.. show me some damn climate papers that go against the purported consensus. fields.author: Steve G
fields.text: It essentially means "Because it is necessary to the security of a free state that we have a well-regulated militia, the right to bear arms shall not be infringed."  That's not simply cause and effect, the second clause is contingent upon the first.  It is like saying "Because I need milk, I am going to go to the store to buy milk."  It is true that I suppose I could go and buy milk for no reason, thus making the second half independent, but the implication is that the second half would be irrelevant without the first.  I wouldn't go to the store to buy milk if it wasn't necessary to do so.  The right to bear arms was put into the Bill of Rights because it was more convenient for people in militias to store their guns in their homes rather than in a communal place, and it was preferred that there would be no standing army at the time, so convenience for a well-regulated militia impelled this right.  Today, the equivalent concept would be a police force (which is armed), not simply every individual citizen.   Also, we have an epidemic of gun violence in the US, and just as the First Amendment is not absolute and we can carve out exceptions for imminent public safety ("fire in a crowded theatre"), we should be able to do the same for the Second Amendment (and all Amendments), since it is causing a public safety hazard.

fields.author: Imma Liberal
fields.text: +Steve G The second amendment is broken up into two parts.First Part - A well regulated Militia, being necessary to the security of a free StateSecond Part - the right of the people to keep and bear Arms, shall not be infringed."These two parts are two completely separate clauses. They are not dependent on each other. Nor has the intent of writing ever given any indication that they are dependent.So why are they in the same sentience? Because grammar. Two clauses appear in the same sentence all the time, this happens because, while they may not be dependent, they are still relevant.Example of two independent clauses in the same sentence: The weather is nice, I shall go to the park.They are relevant, likely even cause and effect, but not dependent. They can both exist in a separate sentence. Just like, "the right of the people to keep and bear Arms, shall not be infringed.", means exactly the same rather it's placed in a sentence on it's own or separately.If you wish to disreguard grammar and continue to claim that they are not separate, hen explain this..."the right of the people to keep and bear Arms, shall not be infringed."The founding fathers intended for "the people" to mean individuals. Do you with to change that? What does, "the people" mean? Is a militia, "the people"? Is a corporation, "the people"? Is the government, "the people"?*"Your friend Bob down the street is not a well-regulated militia, so no, he shouldn't be allowed to have 30 guns in his house with no background checks."*Unless he bought all 30 guns from private sellers, (unlikely) He's had a background check. I actually agree with you on private sells though. All private sales should have to go through an FLL and the 4473 form, including the background check. With that said, it doesn't matter if he has one gun or 30 guns. The fact that you'd even include a number like that makes me question if you're just fear mongering. If he does have 30 guns, he's probably a collector that those guns are likely antiques.

fields.author: samiamrg7
fields.text: +Hadrian Kantor But the ACA is better than nothing. For all it's flaws (and there are many), it HAS made health insurance less expensive for Americans, and it HAS allowed more Americans to get coverage under Medicaid. The costs associated with it's implementation HAS been surpassed by the savings it granted to the American people.

fields.author: samiamrg7
fields.text: +Hadrian Kantor If I had my way, we would just have Socialized medical care, and whatever vasectomies and ED treatments and anything else would be covered too. As it stands, though, the ACA is the best we have, and I want it to be as robust as possible. Instead of removing women's reproductive health from the Employer Insurance Mandate to make things more fair, we should ADD whatever men's reproductive health stuff is missing.

fields.author: samiamrg7
fields.text: +Hadrian Kantor The fact remains that many comparable procedures for women (like sterilization) are more expensive than those for men, and some (like abortion and birth control pills) have no counterpart for men.And is your objection that these things are in the mandate, or that "you" have to pay for them? Because in the former case, you should want the mandate expanded to give coverage for more things you want, not shrunk. In the latter case, I want to be clear in saying that this "mandate" makes it so employers have to provide insurance to employees, which is separate from Medicaid.

fields.author: samiamrg7
fields.text: +Hadrian Kantor The guy I was responding to asked what "social contract" he was under and why it meant he had to pay for birth control. I was merely answering. That doesn't mean the terms of the contract can't be changed, just that that is the way it is right now.And just saying, female sterilization procedures tend to be A LOT more expensive than vasectomies, and birth control pills are not cheap either, that is why they are part of the ACA mandate. A Vasectomy costs at most $1000, but a female sterilization procedure costs at a minimum $1500, and can cost up to $6000. Besides, I would not be surprised if the ACA requires erectile dysfunction to be covered under those insurance plans, and if a "male birth control pill" were ever invented and made easily available, and if it were as expensive as female birth control, it would surely become part of the mandate (the only obstacle, really, would be getting Congress to update the mandate, but they would resist any kind of addition to the ACA regardless of what it is anyway)Now, have anything to say about my comment on embryos?

fields.author: samiamrg7
fields.text: +Hadrian Kantor After conception, there is no more life than there was before. A Zygote is no more or less "alive" than any other diploid cell in the human body, and has scarcely any more individuality. For the first two months of development, an embryo has no resemblance to a human. No organs, no limbs or bones, and no nervous system; just a clump of cells with no form that anyone but an embryologist can recognize. This stage is in which over 90% of abortions are performed.

fields.author: davinodf
fields.text: +AndTheCorrectAnswerIs"Owning" is a loose term.  He often just licenses his name out, especially to developers.  It is called branding.  As stated from a Washington Post article:"Trump has a kind of Midas touch: Many of the businesses he comes in contact with end up with his last name on them, often in large, gilded capital letters. Of the 515 companies that Trump has a part in running, 268 bear his last name, according to a filing with the Federal Election Commission. Yet not all of the buildings emblazoned with Trump's last name are owned by him; for many properties, he merely licenses his name to other developers.D’Antonio says the strategy of branding and franchising is unusual for a businessperson, and more reminiscent of a professional athlete. “Donald is brilliant about turning himself into a walking brand, and he seized that opportunity pretty early,” he says.Trump’s penchant for deploying his name has been a successful marketing strategy, but it also appears to satisfy a deeper desire for fame and accomplishment.In addition to the Trump hotels and casinos, there are Trump-branded steaks (developed for the Sharper Image catalogue, but still served in Trump hotel restaurants), a Trump board game, the now-defunct Trump magazine and Trump Airlines, and a line of shirts and ties called the Donald J. Trump Signature Collection. Trump has put his name on water, Israeli energy drinks, cologne, Virginian wine, vodka, furniture – “almost anything that might be sold as high quality, high cost, and high-class,” D'Antonio writes."And regarding his worth, also just as many articles have noted that he most likely is worth far less than the $10 billion that he claims.

fields.author: AndTheCorrectAnswerIs
fields.text: Let's look at a couple of other facts. Trump Bought the Taj Mahal for $230 Million in 1988. Trump financed the purchase and finishing of the Taj Mahal with junk bonds at 14%. A common practice at the time (it was easier to raise capital for risky ventures thru junk bonds than thru bank financing). The recession in the early 1990's caused almost half of the casinos in Atlantic City to close their doors. Despite this, Trump managed to sell the Taj for $890 million in 1996. As far as what Trump manages goes, he has companies around the world and owns and operates golf courses, hotels, wineries, office buildings, and other real estate ventures. The Trump Organization currently employs 22,450 people. Trump isn't out there "just selling his name". I don't know where people would get this idea.

fields.author: AndTheCorrectAnswerIs
fields.text: +davinodf Trump currently owns 515 companies of which 264 bear his name. There have been NUMEROUS articles in all the top business publications offering insights into Trump's net worth, and they have varied from $4-10 billion depending on the valuation methods used. Trump's tax returns have nothing to do with his net worth. Your tax returns do not show your net worth.

fields.author: davinodf
fields.text: He does not own 515 companies. What he does is sells his name to other businesses. It is the "Trump" brand that he sells. When he actually is in charge of the business operation and not licensing his name out to other businesses, Trump fails. There is no corroborating evidence that he is worth $10 billion other than he says he is. I suspect that is why he does not release his tax returns because he would be embarassed when the public find out that he does not have $10 billion dollars.

fields.author: LabTech
fields.text: +CyanCyborg Well, I probably didn't word it as well as I'd like.  My point was that male circumcision in the 1st world is the only kind where there's some room for discussion, with the other kinds being unacceptable.I mean, yeah, as a male you can always be circumcised later as a surgical outpatient procedure, but it's one of those things where you'd say to yourself 'I'd rather this had already done when I was a baby and I didn't remember it'.I mean, I've already been circumcised, so for me it's a done deal, it was done when I was a baby, and I'm fine about it.  I mean, it's not like I have days where I look at my junk, and wonder what could've been if I had a foreskin, to be honest about it.

fields.author: CyanCyborg
fields.text: +LabTech I like the way you categorized it into four different points. On whole, I'd agree. Though for the last part, my opinion would be that unless there is a major health detriment for not being circumcised, it shouldn't be done until one decides as an adult (in a first world, of course). If I may use vaccines as an analogy, one reason it's done on children is because they could infect those who cannot get vaccines (immune deficient, infants, etc). Consent can take a backseat when lives are at risk; to a certain extent. If all circumcision offers is a minor health benefit that could equally be given by condoms, it isn't necessary to perform on infants.

fields.author: LabTech
fields.text: +CyanCyborg Well, here we have to get into the nuance of the situation.The nuance is that circumcision can be divided into a couple different sets here, between male and female, and 1st world and 3rd world variants.Obviously, the 3rd world variants are right out, as they're barbaric practices done in typically unsanitary fashion by tribal elders, which usually lead to health complications, and are done for no other reason than that's the way it's always been done, and doubly so for girls, as the circumcision is done exclusively to deny female sexual gratification, and enhance it for male gratification.In the 1st world, female circumcision isn't done, unless it's in isolated pockets where 3rd world traditions are still kept, away from the prying eyes of the authorities.  Male circumcision in the 1st world, however, has some credence, in that it's almost exclusively done in a hospital by medical professionals using anesthetic and antiseptic procedures.  There's some evidence to support the notion that removing the foreskin has some health benefits, but there's some evidence to support that removing the foreskin is unnecessary, so there's some room for debate with that variant.All that having been said, on the whole I'm against the notion of genital mutilation.  I'd probably need to read up on the health benefits of male circumcision before I had a definitive position on it.  If there are benefits, I'm inclined to have it done early, so that it's over with, and you have no memory.  If there aren't benefits, then it should be up to the male later in life, as with any other health choice.  Still, parents make plenty of choices for their children before they're old enough to make their own choices, and if they think it's in the child's best interests health-wise, then it should be their choice.

fields.author: CyanCyborg
fields.text: +LabTech Ah, I see. Yeah, I know what you're talking about. As for the male circumcision hypocrisy, I would hope that all of us could at least agree that regardless of any beliefs or possible benefits, there is something inherently wrong about mutilating a baby's genitals, no matter the gender. Do you agree?

fields.author: Brian Linderman
fields.text: +Steven Clark 4. Ultimately what holds all businesses in a libertarian society accountable are three things: 1. The law. 2. the consumer and 3. the market itself. There are still laws in place for a libertarian society, you cant commit fraud, or murder or screw over people for no reason. What those laws are depends on the judicial system you create. Largely who enforces those laws are other private organizations, other businesses and consumers who don't want to be cheated. Also in a libertarian society, the consumer has significantly more market power. The consumer's choice influences the demand for a product and therefore the price of most goods as well. If the majority of people are not willing to buy cars for $50,000, the company must make changes to fit the demand. There is no other force in place to establish subsidies for a company as a cushion. Lastly the market itself makes corrections when something is wrong. if you make a poor decision there is no safeguard to keep you steady. Your stock falls and your investors want their money. If you overvalue your company through fraud the market corrects your mistake and devalues your company below what you are worth. By doing so investors pull out and your company falls to the ground.

fields.author: Brian Linderman
fields.text: +Steven Clark 1. Its not a guarantee, but if there is a demand by the people that these individuals should be cared for then a new business will always take the place of another as long as there is a demand. To suggest otherwise is saying that people will no longer care for the poor or disabled. if that's truly the case, then the system hasn't failed- humanity has failed.2. You have a very thick set of blinders. Yes organizations like SNAP and WIC help people, but do you know why LBJ created SNAP in the first place? It was originally conceived to eradicate hunger. A very tough task. However what is even more interesting in my opinion is how the hunger rate has actually been increasing since the 1970s despite the increase funding given to SNAP. SNAP has failed for 46 years to decrease the rate below 1970 stats. If you continue to throw $90 billion into a program that has failed to decrease rates for 46 years, that's the definition of insanity. Its amazing to me how you think these government programs are so much better yet, private organizations exhibit much higher growth rates, generating an increased rate in aid than gov programs. I'm baffled that you actually believe the government is doing a great job taking care of you.3. You discuss how libertarians value profit over ethics, which is true. However the great reality is in any market, money is everything. You can incentivise businesses to do the ethical thing through money. Now before you say this is a bribe, it works a bit differently. Lets look at FAI for example (back to #2, FAI is a non-profit private organization). Now of course FAI can ask for charity from companies to do the right thing. Or they can tell grocery companies, that if you supply food banks with your products the thousands of people who go to food banks will be eating your products for years. Therefore when they get back on their feet they are more likely to buy from your stores. Now instead of just giving charity, these grocery companies are providing a long term investment to help themselves. FAI is also satisfied because they are given more donations than if they simply begged. This is just basic incentivising in business. It can be done both positive (as seen in example) or negatively (like suggesting if a business makes a bad decision than can be liable to massive costs- so they don't make that decision).

fields.author: Steven Clark
fields.text: So you can guarantee these programs will always be there and available. I think not. That's the problem with relying entirely on private charity as a social safety net, the net might be there one day, the next it might not. And then you have all the selfish bastards who won't donate to charity living off the resources everyone else helped to create. fields.author: Rassa h
fields.text: *I* am saying that the money was burned, based on a factual observation of reality where *OTHERS* are saying the cities are not valuable by not bothering to buy or move into the houses. I'm not the one claiming they're not valuable, the market is. That should be a simple distinction.Luxury and affordable are subjective terms. The most complex, pretty, luxurious, and decorated item is worthless if no one wants to spend any money to buy it off of you. You will burn wealth creating diamonds in the desert, when everyone just wants water. That burned wealth would have been better spent on desalinization or digging wells, just like the wealth burned on those cities would have been better spent on things people need right now.Why are your arguing against such a basic concept?China wanting 6%-7% growth is an example of the tragedy of Keynesianism. They think they can get growth by taking growth away from one sector of the economy and applying (or misapplying) it somewhere else, but all they can accomplish is the same growth at best, and destruction of wealth at best. And it's not just China, it's every country that uses Keynesian economics to guide its government, whether that's through taxing and spending on social programs, or borrowing and spending on infrastructure.But overall, as per the original point, that fucks with the meaning of the GDP. US economy has to collapse its $20 trillion debt before its true GDP emerges.Regarding businesses creating demand, best and classic example of that used in business schools is Apple and their iPhone. But it's not that the demand wasn't there, it was, just not realized. If that demand didn't exist, no one would have bought them.And, again, companies risking their own money, failing, and going away after swallowing the whole risk themselves is OKGovernments risking other people's money against their will, failing, and forcing other people to bail them out regardless is NOT OK.I'm sure you can recognize the obvious moral hazard problem. And that doesn't go away if you just limit it to a little bit of central planning a like in France or USA

fields.author: BlunderCity
fields.text: +Rassa h*"I'm not the one saying the cities in China are not valuable"*You said the money was burned, so yes, you are.*"The market is, by having them be currently unoccupied."*No, what the market says is that there is a mismatch in terms of standards. The apartments built are luxury condos and what people need is affordable housing.But really, it's not an affair of markets. China wants 6%-7% growth and will build just about anything to meet that self imposed target. Building empty cities may be a spectacular but it way well be the safest way of achieving that. I can think of a million ways the Chinese government could screw up with that money. Given the fact that the majority of Chinese citizens live in substandard housing, this appears less risky than what Mao did during the Great Leap forward.*"I'm saying the trend was obviously not there, was miscalculated"*I don't think you understand. China is not really a market economy. It's a planned economy, at least at the government level. So the government mandates that cities be built here and there and they are then bringing in people and jobs into those cities. Obviously this kind of stuff would never fly over here, the government can't go into the countryside and says: Oi! You! You go there and be quiet!", it's just not how things work in Europe or in the US. But in China today, and at other times and places, that's how Communists do things.*"Yes, those cities built 10 years ago have people in them now, but I can guarantee you that the price those people paid to move in was lower than the price the country spent to build, hold, and repair them"*Far from it, they are likely multiple times higher but that's largely the effect of the Chinese property bubble.But really what I'm getting at is that, you don't need to have demand to build things because you can create the demand later. Private businesses in market economies don't do that on a massive scale because they can never justify the risks. But they do it on a smaller scale and try to reassure their investors with carefully crafted business plans and promises of high returns.The exception is when they have deep pockets and plan on losing money for a some time while they are creating the demand. That's the whole idea behind marketing, it's creating a demand that isn't there or changing one need into another need.When Apple launched the iPod, there weren't millions of people crying out for that product, the demand did not exist. More specifically, it was not formulated and Apple did that. Elements of that demand existed (the fact that people had to carry their CDs and mini discs around) but what Apple did is create a product and only then got people hooked on it using clever marketing.And by the way, have you ever heard of failed products and ventures? Every company's got them. Well yeah, those are instances where they fail to create the demand.Command and control governments like China essentially act as giant corporations with deep pockets and a monopoly. Their development is reminiscent of the strategy that was employed in my country, France, during the post war decades. The style of economic management was called "dirigisme". It produced some of the best infrastructure in the world, nuclear weapons, the most advanced civilian nuclear industry, Concorde the supersonic plane, the fastest train in the world, an ancestor to the internet, Ariane rockets into space etc etc...The Chinese government is essentially doing the same thing, trying to design the economy rather than letting it grow organically.

fields.author: Rassa h
fields.text: I'm not the one saying the cities in China are not valuable. The market is, by having them be currently unoccupied. If this was a company building those, that company would be a bankrupted failure now. And I'm not discounting prevailing trends, I'm saying the trend was obviously not there, was miscalculated, and while trends are useful, you don't spend money on a "just in case" future trend, you spend it on a current trend where you are fairly certain you will fulfill it when you're done. Just In Time is a critical aspect of business. You obviously have an economics education. I do as well. But I also have a business finance education, which either you are somewhat lacking, or maybe government economics just simply ignores, which is likely considering that governments don't spend their own money, and have no risk of failure or competition, and that's what you're following too.Yes, maintenance is what prevents entropy, and is what is not happening in these cities, thus their value is going down (I never said zero). Yes, those cities built 10 years ago have people in them now, but I can guarantee you that the price those people paid to move in was lower than the price the country spent to build, hold, and repair them. That's where weal is burned: even if the building do sell (if they don't they're a total loss), the money spent is still less efficient than if that money was spent to build them when they were actually needed. Even people who flip houses don't just buy houses just in case someone will need to move into them later, or sit on them for months or years. Maintenance is expensive. You only buy and repair when you know something will buy it back, or you sell at a loss, or you rent.I'm saying I'm not making guesses about the future because I'm only talking about what has happened and what is happening now, where the money was spent and the cities are sitting empty. You're the one talking about potentials.

fields.author: Rassa h
fields.text: Demand in the future is not current demand. I know there is no demand for those houses because they are still empty after all these months.And, again, investing is investing in an actual unfulfilled demand. Otherwise it's not investing, it's gambling. China obviously failed at analysing trends. But failing to analyse trends isn't the problem. The problem is using other people's money to invest in things against their will. When banks do it, it's highly illegal.

fields.author: BlunderCity
fields.text: +Rassa h*"Houses built with no demand for them have no value"*What makes you think there isn't a demand for it? There sure isn't one this minute or people will have already bought but demand includes anything in the foreseeable future, not just thing that happens this minute.Investing takes a bit of a forward outlook, if you produce something that is already hot, you aren't the first mover and will only get a small slice of the pie, or most likely, will be unable to sell. You have to analyse trends, not the current situation.As a side note, many companies produce things for which there is no demand whatsoever today. Their plan is to create the demand. This is a quite fundamental feature of modern commerce. It's not the 19th century anymore, today, companies are in the business of creating wants, not merely fulfilling needs.And we haven't even touched on the nature of demand in economics. People talk about supply and demand as if they were the same thing, only the mirror image. That's a fundamental misunderstanding of the concept and markets. Supply tends to be definite, I have something and I wanna sell it. Demand is far harder to gauge because a number of things can affect its size and shape of it. Demand is nothing more than future potential for suppliers and that potential is intimately tied to other factors (advertising, fashion tendencies, macroeconomic trends etc...)*"saying that crystal balls are terrible"*But that's exactly what you're doing by claiming a city built in China has no value. You discount all the prevailing trends: You simply look at the fact that no one is moving in these cities and deduct that no one ever will.Wild guesses and crystal balls are not the same as analysing a trend and projecting yourself in the future.*"What you seem to forget or ignore every time I mention it is entropy"*Because there is something called maintenance. It nullifies it at a fairly low cost and buildings last decades.Again, you were wrong in your assumptions for artificially created Chinese cities 10 years ago, they were in exactly the same situation. completely empty and according to you, of a value of zero. Today, they are bustling metropolis. What is to say you're not making the same wrong assumption now? And how can you say you are not making guesses about the future after that?So yes, you ARE talking about future depreciation based on, frankly, a quite simplistic notion that if you can sell right now, you never will.

fields.author: Woo Cheol Shin
fields.text: +Miranda N Cancer is a problem because immune system cannot tell the difference between most cancer cells and normal cells. Boosting immune system does little for cancer. This is a fact. For this reason, vast majority of small molecules found in nature will do little for cancer.I'm not saying all homeopathic treatments are bad. One time a certain homeopathic treatment combined with certain dietary practice significantly outperformed conventional drug treatment for epilepsy. In this case, it's not that the pharma producing conventional epilepsy drug was oppressing alternatives. It's just that the study into the alternative was on-going and incomplete. Now that many studies have concluded, the current conventional treatment for epilepsy includes ketogenic diet combined with new drugs that are more effective and specific.But you are somewhat misguided in your last point. In many cases, pharmas isolate small molecules found in nature, revise their chemical composition slightly to make it more effective or specific (for less side effect) and then patent it. So yeah, pharmas are interested in finding novel compounds in nature. They're just not interested in those that show little promise and certainly not in snake oils. Also a ton of research studies are NOT done by pharmas, but rather by institutions and universities who have no interest in monetary gains.

fields.author: Miranda N
fields.text: +Woo Cheol Shin Homeopathy has not been suppressed by the gov't / pharma companies / scientists *because homeopathic products can be lab-created and patented for profits*. An official move toward regulating it in the US and UK began only recently when the public consumers' complaints against it were accumulating. Also, homeopathy uses the identified harmful substance in each case to allegedly trigger the patient's immune system to counter the disease, which is a fundamentally different mechanism than those discussed in the linked documentary above.Unlike homeopathy and other synthetic drugs, the herbs, baking soda, etc. are sourced directly from the nature and cannot be patented. They are cheap and unprofitable. It's because of the suppression that the lab scientists have been able to market their synthetic drugs & therapies as "the only legitimate treatments".I'm not saying that we have full scientific understandings of the alternatives such as Essiac etc. It's precisely because there's a lack of interests & research from the mainstream scientific community in the field of non-profitable medicines, that i want people to pay more attention to it. The situation is analogous to the historical suppression & criminalization of marijuana. The suppression has benefited the prison-industrial complex & pharma companies & the right-wing politicians (targeting the minority electorates). The more research you do, the more you realize those plants are not only relatively safe but also beneficial and effective against many health problems.

fields.text: +Heiner Privat You're describing regulations.A free market does not mean "free from regulation." Having laws and regulations which apply equally and are applied universally is what Government is there to do and does NOT represent an unfree market.Another way of saying "not free market" is saying "a corrupted market." In other words, you want to get rid of special interests who coerce the powers of Government in their favor.You don't want to get rid of Government itself.

fields.text: +K4316 You're mistaken on this account. I'm not sure where you've learned this history that you've come to understand, but Mosaddegh took emergency power over the Iranian parliament, stripped the Shah of executive powers and centralized decision making to himself.This is a simple timeline:1: Mossadegh attempts to nationalize Iranian oil, removing the Anglo-Iranian Oil Company's (AIOC, now BP) privatization of the Iranian oil resource.2: England pulls all AIOC workers, leaving inexperienced Iranians to work the fields. This caused a drop in oil production, but since the oil was now nationalized, the country was still obtaining greater wealth.3: After England worked to try to recover the deal over Iranian oil, Mossadegh declares England an enemy of Iran and cuts all diplomatic relations.4: England imposes sanctions on Iran, setting up blockades to prevent Iranian imports and exports. England captured at least one oil tanker, citing the oil as "stolen goods." This stopped the export of Iranian oil.5: The British look to US help to resolve the matter. Then Secretary of State in the US Dean Acheson rebuked England's "rule-or-ruin policy" in regards to Iran. It was also stated that the new nationalization agreement in Iran benefited the US greater than the AIOC did.6: In the background of all of this, local Iranian politics were coming to a head. The relationship between Mossadegh and Kashani (Islamic cleric and backer of Mossadegh) became strained; Kashani blaming Mossadegh for not adequately establishing an Islamic state and Mossadegh for causing political instability in the country. This caused an erosion of support from the Islamic nationalist community for Mossadegh -- one of the biggest, if not the largest, supporters for both his position as PM and for oil nationalization.7: Mossadegh had successfully obtained privilege from the Iranian Parliament for emergency powers. He continually eroded the Shah's influence in politics by banning the Shah from engaging in foreign diplomacy, limiting funds and continually removed political power from the Shah.8: The people of Iran, both Islamic nationalists as well as anti-nationalists were against him (and even the less polarized citizenry against him with the economic hardships that the nationalization of Iran's oil had brought on the nation). This was, in part, due to key Iranian citizenry and politicians cooperating with British intrigue as part of Operation Boot. The larger issue was the British sanctions and blockades.9: Mossadegh had his emergency powers extended for another 12 months.10: With Einsenhower now taking presidency, the English leadership was finally able to convince the executive branch in Washington to join in Operation Boot.

In this case if you took two groups randomly chosen, feed one group healthy food and taken their IQ, Then had the other group eat nonhealthy food then take their IQ ect...If the groups were properly chosen at random then the other forces would be ruled out, there should be as many good parents in one groups as the other, there should be as many as (whatever) as the other. The only factor would be the experimental variable.The problem with these type of experiments and the reason why we hear "coorelation and causation" argument is the liberals love to try and find patterns. Group people up, find a pattern in something, call it a problem and then force everyone to solve that problem.

fields.author: Bazuuka Joe
fields.text: +DarKool81​​ +dookdawg214 Exactly. In order to have evidence of causation one must know most, if not all, of the factors involved and produce a mechanism by which to understand how these factors work in tandem to produce a cause. Finding a correlation is literally useless unless you can provide evidence that one is causing the other. There's a reason why the post hoc fallacy is one of the most pervasive fallacies in existence. My main contention is not that the study fails to provide sufficient evidence that there is a causal link between diet and intelligence; my problem is that TYT doesn't even mention it and declares conclusively that there is a causal link. At best, it is a display of ignorance and shows a lack in critical thinking skills; at worst it is intellectual dishonesty.

fields.author: dookdawg214
fields.text: +DarKool81 It's not a mere talking point, you knucklehead. It's a fundamental problem with a lot of research models. And the burden of proof is on the researchers to show that there's a real causation. Did this study identify a biological or physiological mechanism by which higher levels of preservatives have a detrimental impact on neurological activity or cognitive ability? I just scanned a summary of it and I see nothing related to that. All they did was find a correlation. It is much more likely that less-educated (and, correspondingly, less intelligent) parents are less likely to practice good nutritional habits with their children. As a result, you'll find a higher concentration of less-intelligent children who consume fast food. Whether this is the case or not is irrelevant. The fact is, as long as it's a realistic possibility, then it's up to the researchers to correct for this. The burden of proof is on them to demonstrate that there is a real causation.

fields.text: +Tickle Monster Top adviser to Richard Nixon admitted that ‘War on Drugs’ was policy tool to go after anti-war protesters and ‘black people’ The “War on Drugs” was actually a political tool to crush leftist protesters and black people, a former Nixon White House adviser admitted in a decades-old interview published Tuesday.John Ehrlichman, who served as President Richard Nixon’s domestic policy chief, laid bare the sinister use of his boss’ controversial policy in a 1994 interview with journalist Dan Baum that the writer revisited in a new article for Harper’s magazine.“You want to know what this was really all about,” Ehrlichman, who died in 1999, said in the interview after Baum asked him about Nixon’s harsh anti-drug policies.“The Nixon campaign in 1968, and the Nixon White House after that, had two enemies: the antiwar left and black people. You understand what I’m saying,” Ehrlichman continued.*“We knew we couldn’t make it illegal to be either against the war or black, but by getting the public to associate the hippies with marijuana and blacks with heroin, and then criminalizing both heavily, we could disrupt those communities. We could arrest their leaders, raid their homes, break up their meetings, and vilify them night after night on the evening news. Did we know we were lying about the drugs? Of course we did.”*

fields.text: It's worse than that--there's no way that the entire armed populace would all be on the same page, even if they were fighting against a government that could be conquered in such a way (it obviously can't). Everyone has their own definition of the moment that the government has become tyrannical, so some of the populace will be government loyalists who love it, some will be people who dislike government but aren't at the threshold of of an insurrection, some will like certain programs but dislike others, and some will be in full Revolution tilt. So what if I am not really a fan of the government in general, but I stick up for a government program? Would I become the mortal enemy of the revolutionaries? Once this threat was out there, I'd have to defend myself, right? So now there's crossfire chaos between different gradations of unrest. A fully-armed populace would just lead to citizens shooting each other over the disagreements that they had about whether or not to shoot at the government. There's no way that this concept would ever have worked unless you happened to have a government so flagrantly evil that it unified its entire opposition.

fields.text: +Dave MillerYes, CO2 is "plant food", but that's not the problem. That problem is that it's also a greenhouse gas, and it's concentration in the atmosphere is growing very fast. That means Earth is warming up. That's in itself not a big deal, it happened before. The big deal is the speed of the change. What used to take thousands, or millions of years, now happening in decades. That's way too fast, the biosphere can't adapt. That's going to cause mass extinction. The other problem is that the stuff we eat are also living things that need a specific climate to grow. For example if there is too much rain, it washes away the soil, so our crops die. If there is too little, or crops dry out and die. Than we can't feed our domestic animals, so they die too. And because of ocean acidification fish die too. That means no food for us. That leads to mass migration and wars. And also some of the biggest cities on the planet might have an issue with rising sea level.
